segments.text: So this building has from its beginning been intended to be and has been a student funded facility.
A user funded in theory.
We had to go to the Texas legislature to get their okay to charge a mandatory fee.
Any problems there?
Yeah, a lot of them.
Really?
What were they?
Well, initially, Texas had done this two years before for their recreation center, and their fee was $35.
And I'm not sure this ought to be, we had an administrator, I can tell you later who it was, who I think helped write the legislation, sent it forward, didn't ask me, didn't ask anybody else.
Well, this legislation ended up being exactly what Texas had.
And our students had voted for 50, not 35.
So I spent the next two years or year and a half
saying, we're not gonna build this building for 35 because we're gonna end up having a lot less than what we need.
Same thing happened in Texas.
They didn't get what they wanted for their 35.
So we ended up compromising, so to speak,
He would go, we would amend the bill two years later at 50 if we would build, if we would put an auditorium on the building.
At that time we were looking at a leisure pool.
And so we, plus they also funded some money for us too, three and a half million dollars.
So.
All right, then who were the key planners of what would go into the building?
We did,
I personally visited 21 institutions.
Moffett Adams was the chief architect of the system.
He went with me on about 15 of those trips.
So we got a pretty good picture of what was out there.
We selected an architecture firm, Armand Mach out of San Antonio.
I just spelled the last name.
Marmon, M-A-R-M-O-N, and Mock is M-O-K. M-O-K, okay.
Marmon, Mock, two names.
Oh, so it's hyphenated names.
It's not hyphenated.
Not hyphenated, but it's two different people.
Two different names.
They were the architects, but before they were brought on, our staff took the information we got from the surveys.
By that time, we'd done two surveys of needs.
So the students told us what they thought they needed.
We did an analysis of the spaces that we had and what our staff thought we needed.
And then we sat down and wrote out what's called a program that tells the architects what it is that we want in each different space.
all the different kinds of spaces that we need and then what we want to be in space.
And actually, I think we had 11 or 12 authors of that, people that were on staff at that time, the majority of them.
That was Tom Reber, James Walpert, Paula Opal, Mike Waldron, James Nash, I think was on staff then, Rick Hall,
down the list here um there's about 11 different people i know i haven't done it long yet
I guess that's about it.
And the way we did it, and the reason I think it was so successful, is
Everybody who was on staff at that time was assigned space or spaces.
Many of them had more than one space.
And that was theirs from start to finish.
They wrote the program statement.
In that program statement, there's a list of equipment.
They end up speccing out all that equipment for that particular space and going through the purchasing process.
They took it from start to finish.
And they participated in the construction process and watching things as we went.
So that was a good process.
Those folks were probably the most critical.
The other things that we did once, well, then we hired a consultant, Bill Manning from University of California, Berkeley.
And he and Moffitt and I went through the program statement and did all the editing and did all that stuff.
Plus, he participated in all the program design reviews along the way.
So Bill Manning was really critical to, I say Moffitt, myself, Bill, and then the staff people that I mentioned.
As you were dreaming about what this was going to be, what other institutions were the end of the rainbow and what you were hoping to approximate or hoping to copy, equal, surpass?

surpass was probably the word we were looking for because we had a pretty good opportunity with the amount of money that we had available but we looked at and for different reasons different things arizona and arizona state probably two of the newer ones and a particular architect did those and several others so that most of his were very similar
We looked at Tulane and a different set of architects in a little bit different field, probably more closely resembling this one than anything else that's out there.
Texas Tech, because theirs was probably the first building type like this that had the real open effect, and you notice this building is quite open.
We actually visited Missouri, because they did some nice things with their addition, and the old building.
Those are probably the major ones.
As the students let you know what they were hoping for, were there any surprises?
No, not really.
I mean, we were pretty well in tandem with what
The surveys that we got from them and what we were thinking about were pretty darn close.
In terms of what you were hoping to achieve with the new building compared to what we already had, in which areas would we make the greatest improvement?
Swimming facilities?
Weak fitness rooms, swimming.
I think the biggest improvement overall is
is when you walk in the door, the presentation of sports facilities in this kind of a venue are so much different than they are in the traditional venues.
You go over to the Reed Building, and it's not exciting to walk in there.
You walk in here, we just had a tour of all of my colleges.
There was about 90 of them that came down here for the tour.
Our nurse had a facility, supposing, in Austin, and 90 of them came down here to see this place.
And almost to a person, when they walked in the front door, their jaw went, wow.
And that's one of the ways that we can get people interested in an active, healthy lifestyle, is to do it right.
I mean, the wow factor is what we're looking for.
That's what Moffitt said.
When Moffitt told the architects, we want an exciting, exuberant building that attracts people,
We'd get them in the front door.
We'd show them all this stuff.
They can't help but be excited and want to participate.
And the site had already been selected.
No.
Describe how that came about.
Let's go back.
After we did the painting on the program, then we brought the architects on.
They did a design charrette.
It was like a two- or three-day charrette.
The first day we spent just trying to put spaces next to each other that made sense.
The second and third day was with all of our stakeholders, students, physical education staff, coaches, you know, whoever might have, and a lot of other people in the university.
And we met out at Red Cashin's ranch, the little building he had there, the little house.
And they went through discussions.
I mean, there was 50 people there at times.
And that night, we also had a meeting on campus.
And there was probably 100 people that showed up that day, just gathering input that the architects could hear for themselves.
And that thing went on all day.
There was probably 50 or 60 people that went through that.
They'd come and go as they had to leave to go to class and do other things.
But they, at the end of the day, presented like three or four different concepts.
And we all sat there and said, no, you missed the point.
Oh, what have we been saying, you know?
And we were all so disappointed.
I mean, it had been such a productive day, and they did this, and we all sat there and said, oh, no, they just missed the point.
Well, what happened was we went home and they worked all night.
They presented three concepts the next morning and we would have taken any of them.
They were really good.
And we focused in on this concept and then spent the rest of the day doing a little refining of some of the ideas we talked about.
What were the most difficult parts to accommodate in the structure?
Trying to get the spatial relationships right because you have wet areas.
You have an outdoor wet area and an indoor wet area and it's got to relate to the locker room.
The locker room needs to relate to the desk and you don't want it in a wet area.
So that whole thing is more of an art than people would suggest and that's why one of the
Each team of Texas architects had to have a nationally known firm who had built a facility this time before or worked on one.
We had HOK out of Kansas City.
I think that was really key to have some experience in it.
We feel we had some experience, but it's nice to have somebody else there.

And that's why we were pretty liberal in bringing in consultants, because this is a once in a lifetime building, and you need to do it right, because if you don't do it right, you can end up with a headache in a lot of different ways, especially when you're going to pools and gymnasiums and stuff like that.
It can really turn into a headache.
There was a line there.
I set it down, and now I forget where I was going with it.
All right, other other difficult.
You're the sewing area.
Now, actually, I thought our architects pulled together pretty good.
I mean, we spent probably six hours in this trend arranging spaces, what they call bubble diagrams.
And after that was done, that's pretty
Trying to make sure the track was, because we were going for a big track, and I think we got the biggest one in the world.
It was almost a quarter mile, and that ended up working out pretty well.
The arrangement of the racquetball course, we must have drawn up 15 different arrangements, shipped it off to them, or worked with them at meetings.
That was pretty difficult.
Trying to get it just right.
Did you have any preconceived ideas that got changed?
Every one of them.
Oh, okay.
Every preconceived idea got changed.
That was fun working with these guys.
They were really creative, and their ideas were better than mine.
That doesn't happen very often.
They really were good.
They were fun to work with.
How did this location come about?
That was a very political kind of a football, and what the board did was the right thing, is they said, okay, you guys give us a recommendation, the architects.
And they went through a rating process that worked out pretty well.
And although this was not my favorite site because we had intramural fields here, it probably was the best site for this particular building.
My favorite site was Duncan Drillfield.
In reality, this building was too big for that site.
We couldn't have had any associated parking with it.
You could build the building, but no parking.
It really dominated that space up there, too.
One thing they liked about putting the building here, it's a big building, but it doesn't look so big next to Kyle Field and Olsen Field and that Reed building.
If you look over here, if you take any of these buildings,
and you put them over on that other corner of campus, they're not going to fit very well.
They all fit pretty well.
So that was one of the considerations, too.
Did any board members get involved?
Actually, we did several presentations to the board and, I mean, they were always, you know, from day one they were supportive of it.
We did, on these trips that we took, Moffitt and I took videotape and we put together what ended up to be about a six and a half minute presentation that we showed to the board.
Because most people didn't understand
You know, you walk into most facilities, they don't look like this.
They look more like what was over there.
And so we wanted to get the point across of what a recreation center was going to look like.
And the video really helped quite a bit to get the point across to them.
They were all supportive, very supportive of it.
Did any outsider, meaning someone outside the normal area that should have been planting this, did any outsider attempt to affect it?
Romero Galindo.
Who?
Romero Galindo.
He owned Arrowfit at the time.
He didn't want it at all.
He was making, and in the long run, the guy that owned the school gym, all the local club owners didn't lose a lot.
At that time, we had nothing for women's fitness room equipment, so to speak.
I'd say of the kids on this campus that worked out on cardiovascular or in the weight room, probably 70% of them worked out off campus, 30% on campus.
Now it's probably 80% on campus and 20% off.
Probably more than 80% of people who use that room.
That was a big hit for them.
If you were doing it again now, is there anything you'd do differently based on your experience?
In reality, that's one of the questions all of my colleagues ask, what would you do differently?
And I think our planning processes and the architects we worked with, it was open enough and we asked enough questions as we went.
There's one thing we missed probably, two things.
Our outdoor pool area's a little small and we knew that at that point in time we weren't willing to give up parking at the time.
Our outdoor recreation area,
or customer service areas should have been right here.
At that time, we let the overhead door and its ugliness dominate our thought.
Instead of putting it here, we put it there so it's at the back of the building so we don't care what it looks like.
We could have figured that out, we just weren't smart enough at the time, but other than that,
Most people when they build these things don't build them big enough and we really hit the mark pretty close.
There's times when we're overcrowded but most of the time it's we probably hit it closer than anybody did.
So construction started when?
March of 92.
And it's open?
Actually March of 93 because we opened in August of 95.
And what was the reaction nationally?
within among the knowledgeable people to this facility.
Well, it's interesting because there's a little bit of jealousy about that and Georgia opened a facility that they say is 400,000 square feet.
What's this one?

reality is georgia has a lot of physical education and laboratory space and varsity space in there and our building for recreation is bigger than theirs there's again on this tour this weekend they said yours is so much bigger than georgia's so they have a big building yours is bigger and that's the realities i've looked i haven't seen a layout of there but i've seen the listing of the recreation spaces and we have more is is this one looked upon nationally with
It's the best.
It really is.

And what happened, what I was starting to say, there was a young graduate assistant at Maryland, I think, that did an email survey, which facility is the best, which program is the best, and we came out number one in both.
Oh, really?
This is amongst our colleagues.
And then after she published that, then she got ridiculed for it.
Now wait a minute.
We didn't have the opportunity.
Well, everybody had the opportunity because it was on a listserv.
If you're on a listserv, you had the opportunity to respond.
Who would be some of the other close runners up?
Texas is probably number two.
Ohio State is going to be real good.
We spent $36 million on this.
They're going to spend $135 million on this.
Wow.
And they're a school about our size.
They're in, you know, 40,000.
Just a little bit bigger, not much.
Yeah.
But Texas, they built the rec center, and then they remodeled Gregory.
And between the two, they're pretty nice.
They're still in second place.
So Gregory is part of their intramural facilities now?
Right.
And the interesting thing about Gregory is they did the rec center, and it's pretty plain Jane.
Then we did this building, and then they did Gregory.
And if you go out and look at Gregory, you'll see a lot of things that we did here that they tried to copy in Gregory.
Even though it was remodeled, they tried to do it.
And they did a darn good job of it, I think.
The other facilities that have been built recently are probably, except for Georgia, are so small that it doesn't, Arizona and Arizona State still have nice buildings.
Trying to think who, Ohio State's gonna be the next one.
Have there, in intramurals, and particularly with this facility, have y'all ever had any celebrity visitors who have used any of the facilities?
George Bush.
And he's been here several times.
What did he?
He uses the Wake Fitness Room and walks on the track.

first time he came didn't get anything done because students had to talk to him more recently they allowed him to get his work out in what kind of arrangements have to be made by y'all we we get we worked out membership for he and his wife and i think 10 secret service
I think when they came over there was more like four people at a time.
Ten Secret Service members had memberships.
What kind of time notice do y'all get?
None?
No, they just drop in.
They just drop in?
Have there been any students that almost dropped their teeth?
Well, you know, the first time it came, everybody
wanted to chat with him and they did and he was very gracious.

But what they tell me from downstairs is that most of the time when he's come the last two or three times, people have been very cordial and they say hello and you know they're happy, they're really happy he's here but they understand he's here to work out too.
And he's always been very, very cordial out there.
Always, always.
We had some
WWF is over here, the wrestling.
We had about three or four of their people come over and left one afternoon.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
Okay.
See, Ray Childress has been here, I believe.
A few sports celebrities.
Any entertainers that came over to work out before their performance or anything?
Not that I'm aware of.
I would guess that Clay Walker's probably been here, but I don't, you know, we didn't know about him at the time.
He's around here so much.
Any regents and or legislators?
Well, we gave Fred Brown a tour here not too long ago.
Don Powell and...
He's in a group of people in Houston, I forget the name of the group, but this was on their tour one day when they came up here.
They visited here, the Core Center and the Bush Library.
He was in my tour group, so we're giving him a good tour.
All right, looking back over these 27 years, one of the key decisions was obviously this structure.
What were some other, now as you recall, what were some other key decisions y'all made regarding intramurals?
Well, I think the first thing was to try to create sports opportunities for everybody.
revising the rules so it wasn't quite as physical out there and it was more fun by involving women, I think was a key point.
I've continued to focus on quality training, quality sports equipment,

just to quality experience for all our students that was one of the commitments i made when i first came here whatever the best sports equipment is kids are going to have that to play with and now we're trying to do the same thing with facilities too i think building building the glided outdoor field space was critical to the intramural program it still is
And it's now a pretty cool sports club program.
We're continuing to expand out there with play fields.
Things changed so much when this building came online.
Because we went from below the radar scope to being premier.
This building is used almost every
Almost every donor that's on campus gets a tour of this building.
Many, if not all faculty, who are being recruited get a tour of this building.
And I didn't realize how much that was until Evelyn started giving me the numbers we had.
I asked her, how many have kept through here?
The next morning she called, well, we had two this morning.
And this was at a time when we expected that many people to be on campus.
Students, I go to mothers club meetings, I say how many of you have been to the rec center?
I go to fish camp, freshman, how many of you have been to the rec center?
I go to A&M meetings, A&M club meetings, how many of you have been to the rec center?
Our students, we give tours all the time, we did.

300 tours in the first eight months we were open organized tours to 22 000 people it's got a bigger sense but not only do we give tours but our students give tours to their parents to their brothers and sisters to the friends from high school or whatever and there's tours going on here all the time game day is really wild oh i hadn't thought about that all kinds of people down there we had
We'll have 1,500 to 2,000 people participating.
We'll have more than that of people touring the building on game day.
The place is full.
Now, when is the building not open?
We close on Thanksgiving and the Friday after Thanksgiving.
We close on Christmas Eve and Christmas Day, New Year's Eve and New Year's Day.

we used to close on five days a year now it's now maybe seven or eight all right and is it open seven 24 hours a day no we are open at six except on and close at midnight except on saturday we open at eight and sunday we open at uh ten and then in the summertime there are a little bit less than that but but that's our general
So, but it is open seven days a week, at least.
Our philosophy is that recreation facilities need to be open when everybody else is playing.
And that's why we've been there for a while.
We were only closed two days a year.
My staff has said this.
so hard to get people to work, and some of them we've extended that a little bit.

If you were being challenged by a self-appointed critic, say at a legislature or something or other, what argument would you give, what justification would you give for intramurals and its facilities?
First of all, it's a program that's desired by the student body.
Secondly, it's a program that fits in well with college atmosphere.
We've done a study, a grade point study, every semester we've been open.
We've taken our users, our student users, and split them into quartiles and compared their grade point average.
And every semester, undergraduates
The students who use the rec center must have the highest grade point ever.
The only thing that tells you is people who are active are gonna be successful.
So we are not in the way of creating a quality education.
In fact, we are probably one of the best attractors for quality people.
You put up a facility like this, people who really are active say, yeah, I wanna go there, look at that place.
And this is how Ohio State got so much money for theirs.
They were losing ground to, they went from second to fifth choice among Ohio seniors on where to go.
And everybody that they'd lost ground to had built a new rec center.
So they used that as part of the case.
But the reality is, the people that they wanted to get, they weren't getting.
They were getting, the students that they were still getting in Ohio State were their second and third tier students, not the first tier.
Well, it would also be correct to argue that this, in effect, is an investment that the students, if they didn't have this facility, might use their energy and activities in things far less positive.
Exactly.
There's little on this campus that is more positive in the use of leisure time.
And students are going to have leisure time.
They are.
And there's nothing that can be more positive than this.
There's a lot of things that are more negative.
The other part of this is essentially the students are funding this themselves.
It's not like we're asking for money from...
the general tax base.
This is coming from students and their parents.
So that today it's 50th semester?
And what would that $50 buy if they went out to a private recreational facility?
Month and a half.
The last four months here.
Let's see, as another example of a positive,
Give two or three examples of the worst problems you've ever had to work out of intramurals.
There must have been a scuffle or two at some football game or something or other.
Well, the worst one was the worst one that I actually was involved in was up in Texas.
No, no, but here.
Well, let me tell you a story.
We have some scuffles.
You know, we probably, in the 27 years I've been here,
